{{Quote|The breath of the greatest dragon forged the Iron Throne...the swords of the vanquished, a thousand of them, melted together like so many candles...|[[Viserys Targaryen]]|Cripples, Bastards and Broken Things}}

The '''Iron Throne''' is the throne upon which the [[King of the Andals and the First Men]] sits, located in the [[Great Hall (Red Keep)|Great Hall]] of the [[Red Keep]] in the city of [[King's Landing]]. Besides the King himself (or [[Regent|Lord Regent]]) only the [[Hand of the King]] may sit on the Iron Throne. The term is also used colloquially to refer to the monarchy that rules the Seven Kingdoms and the authority of the King (e.g. &quot;Rebellion against the Iron Throne&quot;).

sections.History:
===Background===

The Iron Throne was forged at the order of [[Aegon I Targaryen|Aegon the Conqueror]], the first of the [[House Targaryen|Targaryen Kings]], who [[War of Conquest|conquered six of the seven]] independent kingdoms of Westeros and unified them under his rule - the seventh kingdom of [[Dorne]] was later joined through a marriage alliance. The throne was allegedly forged from the 1,000 swords that had been surrendered to Aegon in the War of Conquest by the lords who had offered their fealty, though the actual number of the swords is less than two hundred.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Climb]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; These were subsequently melted down by the fiery breath of Aegon's dragon, [[Balerion]] the Black Dread, then beaten and bent into a throne of imposing appearance.

At the end of [[Robert's Rebellion]], during the [[Sack of King's Landing]], as the Lannister army overran the city outside of the Red Keep, King [[Aerys II Targaryen]] - the Mad King - refused to surrender, and secretly ordered the city to be burned to the ground with [[Wildfire plot|hidden caches of wildfire]].  To prevent this, his own [[Kingsguard]] Ser [[Jaime Lannister]] killed the Mad King in front of the Iron Throne itself.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Kissed by Fire]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;  Greatly disturbed at having killed the king he had taken the most sacred oaths to defend, Jaime then sat down on the Iron Throne and gave no thought to the carnage going on outside.  Hours later, the main rebel army arrived in the city, and Ned Stark came to the throneroom, where he found Jaime sitting on the throne, and Eddard made Jaime get off of the Iron Throne.  Years later, Jaime's sister Cersei chided Eddard that he could have tried to seize the throne then and there, instead of letting Robert take it, but he did nothing.  Stark never knew why Jaime really killed King Aerys, and seeing him seated on the Iron Throne like that (apparently, out of arrogance) gave Eddard the incorrect belief that Jaime hoped to seize the throne himself some day.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[You Win or You Die]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===[[Season 1]]===

Septa [[Mordane]] quizzes [[Sansa Stark]] on her history lessons while walking through the throneroom, asking her who built the Iron Throne.  Sansa correctly answers that it was Aegon the Conqueror.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Cripples, Bastards and Broken Things]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

Because the king is out hunting, [[Eddard Stark]] sits on the Iron Throne while listening to royal petitioners, in his capacity as Hand of the King.  He hears a report from a [[Joss|peasant refugee]] that Ser [[Gregor Clegane]] has been raiding villages in the Riverlands.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[A Golden Crown]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

Following the death of King [[Robert Baratheon]], his alleged son [[Joffrey Baratheon]] takes his place on the Iron Throne.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[You Win or You Die]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

Far away on the eastern continent in [[Vaes Dothrak]], [[Daenerys Targaryen]] urges her husband Khal [[Drogo]] to help her win back the Iron Throne that her own father once sat upon, for her and Drogo's unborn son that she carries inside her.  At first, Drogo is not very interested:  Westeros is very far away, across the ocean, and to the Dothraki it seems just like a literal chair (without all of the connotations of authority over the Seven Kingdoms associated with it).  After a failed assassination attempt on Daenerys by one of Robert's agents, however, Drogo is deeply offended, and vows to attack Westeros and take the Iron Throne for Daenerys and their son, [[Rhaego]].&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[You Win or You Die]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===[[Season 2]]===

Joffrey continues to jauntily sit on the Iron Throne as the [[War of the Five Kings]] tears apart the realm. He gets up from the throne to menace the captive [[Sansa Stark]] with a crossbow, idly considering shooting her, before relenting that his mother insists she remain alive - so he simply orders his Kingsguard to beat and strip her in front of the entire court.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Garden of Bones]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; Meanwhile, in [[The Stormlands|the Stormlands]] to the south, Robert's younger brother [[Stannis Baratheon]] declares that the Iron Throne is his by right, and all who deny that are his foes.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Garden of Bones]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

During the [[Battle of the Blackwater]], just as the battle seems to be turning against the city's defenders, Cersei Lannister goes to the throneroom to sit on the Iron Throne herself, while holding her younger son [[Tommen Baratheon|Tommen]] sitting on her lap.  Together they await what she fears will be their end, and gets ready to give [[Essence of Nightshade]] to Tommen and herself to painlessly kill them both - as if Stannis is victorious he will have them both tortured to death.  In the nick of time, however, her father Tywin enters the throneroom along with Ser [[Loras Tyrell]]:  the main Lannister army along with reinforcements from [[House Tyrell]] arrived at the last moment and repulsed Stannis's assault, winning the battle&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Blackwater]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===[[Season 3]]===

[[Olenna Tyrell]], in typical fashion, has a low opinion of the throne itself, blithely referring to it as &quot;that ugly iron chair.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Dark Wings, Dark Words]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Petyr Baelish]] remarks to [[Varys]] that the Iron Throne doesn't literally have thousands of swords in it, he has counted and the real number is under two hundred. He says that this is another inflated legend, part of the pageantry and propaganda that supports kings and dynasties but which is in fact illusory.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Climb]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===[[Season 4]]===

Following Joffrey's assassination with poison at [[Purple Wedding|his own wedding]], his younger brother [[Tommen Baratheon]] is crowned as the new king in a ceremony while sitting on the Iron Throne.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[First of His Name]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; Because Tommen is still underaged, however, his grandfather, Hand of the King, and regent [[Tywin Lannister]] later sits on the Iron Throne, while overseeing the [[Trial of Tyrion Lannister]] for the (false) charge of poisoning Joffrey.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Laws of Gods and Men]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;
